# KVPrimaryFunLearning Core Rule (Cross-session)

## Source of truth and scope
- Read requirements in `docs/requirements/BUSINESS_REQUIREMENTS.md`, `docs/requirements/TECHNICAL_REQUIREMENTS.md`, and `docs/planning/IMPLEMENTATION_ROADMAP.md` before changing gameplay behavior.
- Preserve project stack conventions: vanilla TypeScript + Vite + modular CSS + Three.js scenes (no framework migration in feature tasks).
- Keep changes incremental and compatible with existing game flow and UI architecture.

## Quality and correctness
- After substantive edits, run `npm run build` and resolve TypeScript errors before finishing.
- Check lints for edited files and fix newly introduced diagnostics.
- For gameplay changes, verify both success and failure paths (correct, wrong, timeout, completion).
- Do not leave placeholder behavior when replacing a demo scene; ensure feature-complete integration in `play.ts`.

## Performance and stability
- Favor lightweight procedural meshes/textures and avoid heavy model assets unless explicitly requested.
- In Three.js code, always clean up resources (`geometry`, `material`, textures, listeners, RAF) in `dispose()`.
- Keep renderer settings production-safe (`ACESFilmic`, controlled exposure, bounded pixel ratio, soft shadows).
- If dev runtime shows stale dependency errors from Vite optimizer, clear `node_modules/.vite/deps` cache and re-test.

## Educational content and UX
- Keep Vietnamese copy age-appropriate, clear, and encouraging for primary learners.
- Align game timing and difficulty with established balancing rules (for level easy, keep agreed standard timing).
- Provide immediate feedback on user action (visual/audio/state text), not silent waiting.

## Documentation discipline
- When behavior, architecture, or UX conventions change, update relevant docs in `docs/` in the same task.
- Keep `docs/status/CURRENT_STATE.md` updated after major behavior/system changes.
- Validate docs completion against `docs/workflow/DOCS_DEFINITION_OF_DONE.md`.
